5a. ¿El sistema es BIBO estable?

Para saber si un sistema es BIBO estable se busca que la parte real de las raices de la función de transferencia sean negativas, por lo que primero se aplica Lapalace y se obtiene :
Las raíces de la función son raíces complejas por lo tanto el sistema es BIBO inestable.

Se hace la convolución.

Reproduzca los resultados de la MATLAB session 4 del libro de Lathi.

M4.1

% function [H] = MS4P1(B,A,omega);
% H=polyval(B,j*omega)./polyval(A,j*omega);
% end

M4.2

omega_c=2*pi*3000;
C=1e-9;
R=1/sqrt(C^2*omega_c^2)
R = 5.3052e+04
f=linspace(0,20000,200);
B=1;
A=[R*C 1];
Hmag_RC=abs(MS4P1(B,A,f*2*pi));
plot(f,abs(f*2*pi)<=omega_c,'k-',f,Hmag_RC,'r--')
xlabel('f [Hz]');
ylabel('|H_{RC} (j2/pi f)|');
axis([0 20000 -0.05 1.05]);
legend('Ideal','First Order RC')

M4.3

R=sqrt(2^(1/10)-1)/(C*omega_c)
R = 1.4213e+04
B=1;
A=poly(-1/(R*C)*ones(10,1));
A=A/A (end);
Hmag_cascade=abs(MS4P1(B,A,f*2*pi));
figure
plot(f,abs(f*2*pi)<=omega_c,'k-',f,Hmag_RC,'r--',f,Hmag_cascade,'b--')
xlabel('f [Hz]');
ylabel('|H_{RC} (j2/pi f)|');
axis([0 20000 -0.05 1.05]);
legend('Ideal','First Order RC','Tenth-order cascaded RC')
N=10;
poles=roots([(1j*omega_c)^(-2*N),zeros(1,2*N-1),1]);
B_poles=poles( find(real(poles)<0));
A=poly(B_poles);
A=A/A(end);
Hmag_B=abs(MS4P1(B,A,f*2*pi));
figure
plot(f,abs(f*2*pi)<=omega_c,'k-',f,Hmag_RC,'r--',f,Hmag_cascade,'b--',f,Hmag_B,'g--')
xlabel('f [Hz]');
ylabel('|H_{RC} (j2/pi f)|');
axis([0 20000 -0.05 1.05]);
legend('Ideal','First Order RC','Tenth-order cascaded RC','Tenth-order Butterworth')

M4.5

omega_0 = 3000*2*pi; % Filter cut---off frequency
psi = [9 27 45 63 81].*pi/180; % Butterworth pole angles
f = linspace(0, 6000, 200); % Frequency range for magnitude response calculations
Hmag_SK = zeros(5,200); % Pre-allocate array for magnitude responses
for stage = 1:5
Q = 1/(2* cos(psi(stage))); % Compute Q for current stage
% Compute and display filter components to the screen:
disp([ 'Stage ',num2str(stage),' (Q = ',num2str(Q),'): R1 = R2 = ',num2str(56000),', C1 = ' ,num2str(2*Q/(omega_0*56000) ),', C2 = ' ,num2str(1/(2*Q*omega_0*56000) ) ] ) ;
B = omega_0^2; A = [1 omega_0/Q omega_0^2] ; % Compute filter coefficients
Hmag_SK(stage,:) = abs(MS4P1(B, A, 2*pi*f)); % Compute magnitude response
end
Stage 1 (Q = 0.50623): R1 = R2 = 56000, C1 = 9.5916e-10, C2 = 9.3569e-10 Stage 2 (Q = 0.56116): R1 = R2 = 56000, C1 = 1.0632e-09, C2 = 8.441e-10 Stage 3 (Q = 0.70711): R1 = R2 = 56000, C1 = 1.3398e-09, C2 = 6.6988e-10 Stage 4 (Q = 1.1013): R1 = R2 = 56000, C1 = 2.0867e-09, C2 = 4.3009e-10 Stage 5 (Q = 3.1962): R1 = R2 = 56000, C1 = 6.0559e-09, C2 = 1.482e-10
plot (f, Hmag_SK, 'b', f, prod (Hmag_SK), 'k: ')
xlabel ( 'f [Hz] '); ylabel ( 'Magnitude Response ')

M4.6

% function [C_N] = MS4P3(N);
% C_Nm2 = 1; C_Nm1 = [1 0]; % Initial polynomial coefficients:
% for t = 2:N;
% C_N =2*conv([1 0], C_Nm1) - [zeros (1, length (C_Nm1) - length(C_Nm2) + 1), C_Nm2];
% C_Nm2 = C_Nm1; C_Nm1 = C_N;
% end
% end
omega_c=2*pi*100;
R=1;
N=8;
K=N:-1:0;
epsilon=sqrt(10^(R/10)-1);
CN=MS4P3(N).*((1/(1j*omega_c)).^K);
CP=epsilon^2*conv(CN,CN);
CP(end)=CP(end)+1;
poles=roots(CP);
i=find(real(poles)<0);
C_poles=poles(i);
plot(real (C_poles),imag(C_poles), 'kx ');
axis equal;
axis(omega_c*[-1.1 1.1 -1.1 1.1]);
xlabel('\sigma');
ylabel('\omega');
A=poly(C_poles);
B=A(end)/sqrt(1+epsilon^2);
omega=linspace(0,2*pi*2000,2001);
H=MS4P1(B,A,omega);
plot(omega/2/pi,abs(H),'K');
grid on
xlabel('F [Hz]');
ylabel('H(J2\pi f');
axis([0 2000 0 1.1]);
k = [1:N];
xi = 1/N*asinh(1/epsilon);
phi = (k*2-1)/(2*N)*pi;
C_poles = omega_c*(-sinh(xi)*sin(phi)+j*cosh(xi)*cos(phi));
plot(real(C_poles),imag(C_poles), 'kx ');
axis equal;
axis(omega_c*[-1.1 1.1 -1.1 1.1]);
xlabel( '\sigma '); ylabel( '\omega ');
